Photoconductive detectors are fabricated from AlGaN alloys in thin-film form with interdigitated metal contacts placed on the surface of the material to maximize light transmission while minimizing transit time. These photoconductive detectors, as opposed to photovoltaic ones, exhibit the important advantage of internal gain, which reduces the requirement for low-noise preamplifiers. The gain is due to the fact that the minority carriers are trapped while the majority carriers go around the circuit many times before recombination. Of course the fundamental principle in all detectors is that the gain times the bandwidth should be constant. Thus, if the detector is designed to have high photoconductive gain, its response time is long. The photoconductive gain is given by the expression: (6)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
